{"hash":"e6c0d1b887cc7b956390a44904eb7fa5c08bd4cb","data":{"post":{"title":"How to fix \"Unknown command nvm\" on Linux","date":"January 17, 2021","content":"<p>Here is how you can fix \"nvm: command not found\" on Linux.</p>\n<h2 id=\"1-verify-that-you-have-nvm-installed\"><a href=\"#1-verify-that-you-have-nvm-installed\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>1. Verify that you have nvm installed</h2>\n<p>sudo find / -name \"nvm.sh\"</p>\n<p>This command should return the full path of the file.</p>\n<p><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loading\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg fill='none' viewBox='0 0 816 517' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' xmlns:xlink='http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink'%3e%3cdefs%3e%3cfilter id='__svg-blur-5d7c17231c66c88196a0b737be377d5d'%3e%3cfeGaussianBlur in='SourceGraphic' stdDeviation='40'/%3e%3c/filter%3e%3c/defs%3e%3cimage x='0' y='0' filter='url(%23__svg-blur-5d7c17231c66c88196a0b737be377d5d)' width='816' height='517' xlink:href='data:image/png%3bbase64%2ciVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAEAAAAApCAYAAACFki9MAAAACXBIWXMAAAsTAAALEwEAmpwYAAAEsklEQVRo3u1aW1NbVRQ%2b5EIIudCUq%2bVOIFwMIJdzEkgI93CxDDBUFB%2bi4gTpC8P0QaXjH%2bj40qkP%2bmI740urlXZGHZ98cPwj/SVm%2bX0bdgyMUDuTMtEcZj72XmvtnbPXty5nM8T4PDUvq/NW7u7Hplg34xK7kxRrFPOYJZZVHJimKalUSqampiSZTKp5IpGQyclJNZ%2bdnc3rOJ%2bZmZHp6Wml4/p4PF60swC5U8jo6OgL45vpdO7dmzF59IUp5nsTYt1PiTViKQJMy1SbYrGYckLjvHNax3Vap2W9d35%2bXtbW1mRlZUXW19dlYWFBYWNjQ4G21dVVWV5elnQ6rcalpSVlm5ubO/N5RUJufHxcDBNRGTfjucG3YpKMJ2TKTKoFjA5B9ukAI0EwShMTE8rGdZQZKR0l6rlOO66J4sPGxsbyoEx7oVwI2grnRcwAnQV87p/G4cGBvHPrFlIuJfu39yW7l1Xpt7W1Jfv7%2b7K7u6uc29nZkWw2q%2bRMJqPmdH57e1uOjo5UVOk87YeHh7K5uZknpBTBIKIExGhvb5eOjk6AY0ceJ/oO6erqysta19nZqcB5W1tbXqf3hsNhtU/vuSoUnvOyNTxzJBJRgTXwI%2bWIuro6WVxcFMPp8ojHE5RAwK%2bixrStqamR5uZmFdVoNCqtra3i9/ulsrJSgsGg9Pf3y%2bDgoIo0dWSWOu73er0yNDSkWL4qZ3gGPjcQCEh1dbWCx%2bNRep/Pl9dVVVWp0eVy/U2A24nNbr%2bEQEBvd7e8CUdC166JB5sb6%2bsl0tMjDRgpuxwO8eFD%2bqAbQAqFkU48AB/SAx2JIHkceQDaKioqFAoPXCjr%2bfk1rwI6xOfROTpNRzk6nU5xu90KtHOkjfPa2toTAsq%2bBHYQ7QMw9yXY%2bQqGJ8Ax8AzRfg4GjxEZjpQfQ/8Q8teI%2bINQSD69fl2Gb9yQJmRCdGBANRimIh/A0mGZtLS0qIbDkuCc2dGNTGNJcc3IyIg0NTWpOde9bsd1puUJ%2bB0EPMah7yFl7iKV9uBcBoTsIpUzmH%2bIusrC0SxSJotD38G6eyDkAQj5CetegIg1lI0P9qbGRpWODthC0JOQhoYG1RvYU0gAiSBIAHtMb2%2bv1KPEWEJcc%2bUZEMElJIrrZxjXz0pEwIdIvoGLjQMHM0CMd3hY6vDe9KKxOfr6pJq3J4wGGqOBC8ptMPrwP1gC%2bR7wK4TfENGfMT4FnsOhJ4jg9xh/gEwcw/4UMu0/YmRZPAO%2bg/wH8AvTCnucgG56zILLcNEavf9lMM7N/ynVKy7Qc2TWKQLSEBLAZ8iEj5CCb2P%2bPvABsAdkX4JPgL4CAhxXAD7HQ7JO4UKAWHoa7PZqHfR8G%2bg3gbadIcDwBvHLKfcffSuLuBIrprCxlNPXAQQBL%2bAH3Hitsaew7/CVzPsAmzGdp546gjrKHPMl4Dj90HY0qBAaH%2bfOV0RFiRBz2V2isDTPNMETYxnfA/4Ne2VBQKnidQWmpAnQTvNyxKZVtgTwL0x29LItgYsuM2XVA8q%2bCdoE2ATYBNgE2ATYBNgE2ATYBNgE2ATYBNgE2ATYBBT/n6PlnAH8Npqhv0RQ%2bK%2bl/zPoK7OABPB7i38BGBiAYm92AS8AAAAASUVORK5CYII=' /%3e%3c/svg%3e\" width=\"816\" alt=\"using find\" data-srcset=\"/assets/static/find.82a2fbd.3b1bd3217657bd6ba811ec4d865710d9.png 480w, /assets/static/find.6dd9030.3b1bd3217657bd6ba811ec4d865710d9.png 816w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 816px) 100vw, 816px\" data-src=\"/assets/static/find.6dd9030.3b1bd3217657bd6ba811ec4d865710d9.png\"><noscript><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loaded\" src=\"/assets/static/find.6dd9030.3b1bd3217657bd6ba811ec4d865710d9.png\" width=\"816\" alt=\"using find\"></noscript></p>\n<p>If it does not return the full path to then the installation of nvm probably was not successful.</p>\n<h3 id=\"verify-that-nvm-was-installed-under-the-correct-path\"><a href=\"#verify-that-nvm-was-installed-under-the-correct-path\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>Verify that nvm was installed under the correct path</h3>\n<p>Also, notice that the .nvm directory is located in my home directory. Your .nvm directory should be\nlocated in your home directory as well.</p>\n<p>If it's not, you probably installed .nvm with the wrong user or using sudo.\nIn this case, you should try to reinstall nvm.</p>\n<p>Use this command if you are unsure where your home directory is.</p>\n<pre class=\"shiki\" style=\"background-color: #2e3440ff\"><code><span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #88C0D0\">echo</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">HOME</span></span></code></pre>\n<h3 id=\"verify-that-you-restarted-your-terminal-session\"><a href=\"#verify-that-you-restarted-your-terminal-session\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>Verify that you restarted your terminal session</h3>\n<p>To use nvm after installation you need to restart your terminal session.\nSimply close your current terminal and open a new terminal.</p>\n<h2 id=\"2-source-nvm-for-your-shell\"><a href=\"#2-source-nvm-for-your-shell\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>2. Source nvm for your Shell</h2>\n<p>Now you need to source the nvm.sh file, so that nvm can be used in the shell.</p>\n<h3 id=\"for-bash\"><a href=\"#for-bash\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>For bash</h3>\n<p>Add this to your .bashrc</p>\n<pre class=\"shiki\" style=\"background-color: #2e3440ff\"><code><span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">export</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> NVM_DIR=</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">HOME</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">/.nvm</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span></span>\n<span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">[</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">-s</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">NVM_DIR</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">/nvm.sh</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">]</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">&amp;&amp;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #EBCB8B\">\\.</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">NVM_DIR</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">/nvm.sh</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">  </span><span style=\"color: #616E88\"># This loads nvm</span></span></code></pre>\n<p>Remember to also use the correct path, it can differ from the path that you see here.\nAlso notice that you have to enter the nvm directory instead of the full path to the NVM_DIR variable.</p>\n<p>After adding the two lines of configuration you should restart your terminal emulator.\nNow you should be able to use nvm.</p>\n<h3 id=\"for-zsh\"><a href=\"#for-zsh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>For zsh</h3>\n<p>Add this to your .zshrc</p>\n<pre class=\"shiki\" style=\"background-color: #2e3440ff\"><code><span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">export</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> NVM_DIR=</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">HOME</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">/.nvm</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span></span>\n<span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">[</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">-s</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">NVM_DIR</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">/nvm.sh</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">]</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">&amp;&amp;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #EBCB8B\">\\.</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">NVM_DIR</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">/nvm.sh</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&quot;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">  </span><span style=\"color: #616E88\"># This loads nvm</span></span></code></pre>\n<p>Now restart your terminal emulator and that's it, you should be able to use nvm now.</p>\n<h3 id=\"for-fish\"><a href=\"#for-fish\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>For fish</h3>\n<p>This one is a bit more difficult. Since fish is not fully <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/POSIX\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">POSIX</a>\ncompliant, it is not compatible with the nvm.sh file nvm provides.</p>\n<p>To make it work anyway, we can use <a href=\"https://github.com/edc/bass\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Bass</a>. It allows us to use the nvm.sh\nfile in the fish shell without any modifications.</p>\n<p>We'll use the <a href=\"https://github.com/jorgebucaran/fisher\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Fisher</a> plugin manager to make the installation process as easy as possible.</p>\n<h4 id=\"1-install-fisher\"><a href=\"#1-install-fisher\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>1. Install Fisher</h4>\n<pre class=\"shiki\" style=\"background-color: #2e3440ff\"><code><span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">curl -sL https://git.io/fisher </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">|</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #88C0D0\">source</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">&amp;&amp;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> fisher install jorgebucaran/fisher</span></span></code></pre>\n<h4 id=\"2-install-bass\"><a href=\"#2-install-bass\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>2. Install Bass</h4>\n<pre class=\"shiki\" style=\"background-color: #2e3440ff\"><code><span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">fisher install edc/bass</span></span></code></pre>\n<h4 id=\"3-source-nvm\"><a href=\"#3-source-nvm\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"icon icon-link\"></span></a>3. Source nvm</h4>\n<p>Now that bass is installed, add this to your config.fish file:</p>\n<pre class=\"shiki\" style=\"background-color: #2e3440ff\"><code><span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">function</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #88C0D0\">nvm</span></span>\n<span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">   bass </span><span style=\"color: #88C0D0\">source</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">HOME</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">/.nvm/nvm.sh --no-use </span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&#39;</span><span style=\"color: #A3BE8C\">;</span><span style=\"color: #ECEFF4\">&#39;</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\"> nvm </span><span style=\"color: #81A1C1\">$</span><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9\">argv</span></span>\n<span class=\"line\"><span style=\"color: #D8DEE9FF\">end</span></span></code></pre>\n<p>Remember to also use the correct path.</p>\n<p>That's it! Now you can use nvm in fish.</p>\n","tags":[{"title":"Linux","path":"/tag/Linux/"},{"title":"nvm","path":"/tag/nvm/"}]}},"context":{}}